<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12113b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12113b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12113b"> 113(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Columbanus in forest / of Luxeuil = Adam</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le livre des Ecritures suspendu dans un sachet sur l&apos;&eacute;paule, selon la coutume des moines de son pays, Colomban s&apos;enfon&ccedil;ait dans la for&ecirc;t et se donnait aux douceurs de l&apos;oraison; il se repliait sur lui-m&ecirc;me et conversait famili&egrave;rement avec son Dieu. Et, devant cet homme que ses h&eacute;ro&iuml;ques renoncements avaient presque remont&eacute; &agrave; la condition d&apos;Adam, se renouvelaient, s&apos;il faut en croire Jonas, les sc&egrave;nes gracieuses de l&apos;Eden, telles que les asc&egrave;tes de l&apos;Erin se les repr&eacute;sentaient dans leurs l&eacute;gendes. <br><font color="green">[<mark>With the book of Scriptures hanging in a small bag on his shoulder</mark>, according to the custom of the monks of his country, <mark>Columbanus went deep into the forest [at Luxeuil]</font></mark>and surrendered himself to the sweetness of prayer. He retired within himself and conversed familiarly with his God. And, before this man &mdash; <mark>whose heroic renunciations had almost brought him to the condition of Adam</mark> &mdash; if we are to believe Jonas&mdash;the gracious scenes of Eden were renewed, such as those depicted by the ascetics of Erin in their legends.] <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 36-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
